	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>NGOs welcome PNA eco-labelled fishery</h1>

			
			<h4>
												19 February 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The certification of the PNA (Parties to the Nauru Agreement) free-schooling skipjack tuna fishery has been welcomed by WWF and ISSF, although ISSF had initially opposed MSC certification. ‘This is the largest tuna fishery to have achieved MSC certification, a standard that will help ensure this valuable fishery can achieve a healthy state,” said a WWF representative, while ISSF pointed out that the certification was only subject to conditions. These relate to the benchmarks and accomplishments that the fishery must meet during the next five years in order to maintain the certification.</p><p>The main challenge identified by both organisations is that the PNA must manage the skipjack fishery in its waters taking into account catches in waters outside of PNA control. Both organisations also see the role of the Western and Central Pacific Fisheries Commission (WCPFC) as vital, as it must implement reference points that identify an acceptable level of fishing, as well as a population size that should be maintained.</p><p>ISSF drew particular attention to the fact that ‘the fishery’s chain-of-custody – a key component of product traceability – has not been certified. Proper chain-of-custody supervision is critical in preventing illegal fishing as well as mislabelling’. The MSC requires this specifically for the PNA: ‘there needs to be credible monitoring to ensure that fishers and processors keep tuna caught in free-swimming school sets in a specifically defined area of the ocean and by specific boats, separate from tuna caught with other methods, areas and boats not included in the certification. As most vessels make both types of sets in a fishing trip and the trip may cross into uncertified areas, this separation and monitoring must be maintained through all stages of fishing, unloading the vessel, and processing’.</p><p>Both organisations offer their support to work with the WCPFC, PNA and its member states in order to meet the conditions of the certification and help to ensure that the PNA fishery can maintain its MSC certification.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ISSF editorial, ‘Certification of chain-of-custody, the next challenge for PNA’, 13 January 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://iss-foundation.org/2012/01/18/issf-certification-pna-msc-chain-of-custody-next-challenge/" target="_self">http://iss-foundation.org/2012/01/18/issf-certification-pna-msc-chain-of...</a></p><p>WWF press release, ‘WWF congratulates Pacific islands for certification of major tuna fishery’, 10 January 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/?203069/WWF-congratulates-Pacific-Islands-for-certification-of-major-tuna-fishery" target="_self">http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/?203069/WWF-congratulates-Pacific-Islands-...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>This article highlights how the process of obtaining eco-certification and being able to make use of an eco-label is both complex and demanding. First of all, the fisheries must be sustainably managed, which means in this case that the PNA will need to take into account catches in waters outside of PNA control. Fortunately, since its inception, the PNA has already shown its capacity to develop a collaborative approach and to assist the whole region in managing its tuna resources sustainably. Secondly, the traceability throughout the whole chain of custody must also be guaranteed. It needs to be noted that, at least for PNA eco-labelled products that will be sold on the EU market, the compulsory catch certificate, linked to the IUU regulation, already provides a high level of traceability. Other ACP fishing nations may wish to consider adopting a similar approach in order to promote the sustainable management of their fishing resources and improve traceability along the fisheries value chain.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
